Q38. LoRa & LPWAN – Long Range IoT

LPWAN stands for Low Power Wide Area Network.
It is a wireless communication technology designed for IoT devices that need to send small amounts of data over long distances while using very little power.
It is commonly used in smart agriculture, smart cities, water meters, and environmental monitoring.
LoRa (Long Range) is a popular LPWAN technology.
It achieves long-distance communication with low power using a technique called Chirp Spread Spectrum (CSS).
LoRa uses different Spreading Factors (SF7 to SF12).
A higher spreading factor sends data more slowly but increases communication range and improves signal reception in weak network conditions.
A lower spreading factor provides faster data transmission but covers a shorter range.
This balance helps battery-powered IoT sensors operate for years.
Compared with other technologies,LoRa offers very long range, low power consumption, and low data rates.
Zigbee provides shorter range but supports fast communication through mesh networks, making it suitable for home automation.
Z-Wave also has shorter range and is mainly used for smart home devices such as locks, lights, and sensors.
A real-world example in India is the use of LoRaWAN-based smart metering and smart-city IoT systems.
Such deployments enable remote monitoring of utilities and city infrastructure, reducing manual work and improving efficiency.
